properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow at times heavy is expected on Saturday. Snow at times heavy, is expected to begin Friday overnight persist throughout the day on Saturday and taper off to scattered flurries by Saturday evening. Snowfall totals of 15 to 20 centimeters are expected with this event, however snow totals will be less in areas where the snow mixes with rain. Strong wind gusts and blowing snow are also possible in some areas that may reduce visibility. This snow event is associated with a strengthening low pressure system that is forecast to track eastwards across northern Ontario on Saturday and Saturday night. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2020-10-31T01:18:40-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snow likely on Saturday. Snow is forecast to begin early Saturday morning and may become mixed with rain early Saturday evening before tapering off to flurries near midnight. At this time, forecast guidance suggests that up to 10 centimeters of new snowfall can be expected by Saturday evening, however in the northernmost sections of the region where the precipitation will remain entirely as snow, snowfall amounts could be closer to 15 centimeters. This heavy snow is associated with a strengthening low pressure system that is forecast to track across northern Ontario Saturday and Saturday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 25 cm is expected. A further snowfall of 5 to 10 cm is expected this morning. A low pressure system crossing the central interior this morning will give a further 5 cm of snow to Williston and up to 10 cm elsewhere this morning. The snow will end by afternoon as the low moves into Alberta. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant amounts of snow are expected. The first significant storm of the season will give snowfall amounts of 20 to 30 cm by Saturday afternoon. A Pacific frontal system will move into the Gulf of Alaska tonight and then remain stationary over the area this weekend. Light snow will develop for this afternoon and then become heavy at times tonight. Gusty south winds will also cause local blowing snow on Saturday. Warmer air associated with the system may cause a changeover to rain Saturday afternoon before switching back to snow Saturday evening. Another snowstorm is possible by Sunday night. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.
Expires: 2020-10-31T05:16:22-00:00

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 20 cm is expected. A deepening low pressure system will move across the BC central coast later tonight. Heavy snow associated with this system has begun over many North Coast inland communities and is expected to continue until early Friday morning. Near Kitimat, precipitation will stay as a mix of wet snow and rain throughout the night with lesser snowfall accumulations expected. For areas north of Kitimat, snowfall amounts up to 20 cm are possible before the snow eases early Friday morning. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A strong low pressure system has brought very strong winds to the central coast last night. Northwest winds of 90 km/h will continue over exposed coastal sections early this morning. Winds will gradually abate throughout this morning as the low moves farther inland. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2020-10-30T17:14:46-00:00

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Strong southwest winds gusting to 90 km/h early this morning. A deep low pressure system over the central coast of BC will move across the central interior today. Winds will rise to 70 km/h gusting to 90 early this morning. Communities near and within the Coast Mountain Range will be the most likely to receive the severe winds. Winds will ease late this morning as the low moves eastward. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
